E-F-S: shared file storage.

E-F-S is a managed N-F-S version four filesystem that many Linux instances mount at the same time, across availability zones, across accounts, and even from on-premises over Direct Connect or V-P-N. Unlike E-B-S, it's regional: data is replicated across multiple availability zones automatically, capacity grows and shrinks elastically, and you pay per gigabyte stored with no provisioning. Clients connect through mount targets, one per availability zone, each a private I-P in your V-P-C, with security groups controlling which instances can connect. Every mount target resolves to the same filesystem, so a write through any one is immediately visible through all the others. It's Linux and POSIX only; Windows clients need F-S-x for Windows instead. Typical uses are content shared across web servers, Linux home directories, shared configuration across an Auto Scaling Group, and container volumes for E-C-S and E-K-S via the E-F-S C-S-I driver.

There are two orthogonal knobs. Performance mode is set at creation: General Purpose gives the lowest latency and suits almost everything, while Max I/O has higher latency but scales to thousands of concurrent clients, for big analytics and media pipelines. Throughput mode is changeable any time: Elastic auto-scales to demand and is the right default for new filesystems, Bursting scales its baseline with stored size, and Provisioned gives fixed throughput for a small dataset that needs a lot of it.

E-F-S also has its own tiering, by last-access time: Standard, then Standard-I-A at about ninety-two percent cheaper, then Archive at about ninety-five percent cheaper, with an optional rule to promote a file back on access. And E-F-S One Zone is a single-availability-zone variant, about forty-seven percent cheaper, for dev-test or data already backed up elsewhere; if that zone fails, the filesystem is unavailable, and a lost zone means lost data.
